<paragraph id="8BD936A3FFB0FF92FF41FE4DFC150119" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">
Originally known from Hawaii, 
<taxonomicName id="4C664D20FFB0FF92FD98FE4EFD4C02D1" baseAuthorityName="Hyman" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[542,719,477,501]" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Endeavouria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="septemlineata">
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FD98FE4EFD4C02D1" box="[542,719,477,501]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">E. septemlineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also present in the 
<collectingCountry id="F3717633FFB0FF92FC32FE4DFBC102D1" box="[948,1090,477,501]" name="Cook Islands" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Cook Islands</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3717633FFB0FF92FBCBFE4DFB1202D1" box="[1101,1169,477,501]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, Tahiti, and 
<collectingCountry id="F3717633FFB0FF92FA94FE4DFAC002D1" box="[1298,1347,477,501]" name="Italy" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Italy</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFF74B52FFB0FF92FAD6FE4DFE9D013D" author="Justine, J. - L. &amp; Lemarcis, T. &amp; Gerlach, J. &amp; Winsor, L." pageId="2" pageNumber="449" pagination="297 - 300" refId="ref2672" refString="Justine, J. - L., Lemarcis, T., Gerlach, J. &amp; Winsor, L. (2018 a) First report of the land planarian Endeavouria septemlineata (Hyman, 1939) (Platyhelminthes, Tricladida, Continenticola, Geoplanidae) in French Polynesia. Zootaxa, 4450 (2), 297 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4450.2.10" type="journal article" year="2018">
Justine 
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FF11FD92FF53013D" box="[151,208,513,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">et al.</emphasis>
2018a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF74B52FFB0FF92FEAAFD91FE64013D" author="Mori, E. &amp; Magoga, G. &amp; Panella, M. &amp; Montagna, M. &amp; Winsor, L. &amp; Justine, J. &amp; Lou &amp; Menchetti, M. &amp; Schifani, E. &amp; Melone, B. &amp; Mazza, G." box="[300,487,513,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" pagination="205 - 216" refId="ref3172" refString="Mori, E., Magoga, G., Panella, M., Montagna, M., Winsor, L., Justine, J. Lou, Menchetti, M., Schifani, E., Melone, B. &amp; Mazza, G. (2022) Discovering the Pandora's box: the invasion of alien flatworms in Italy. Biological Invasions, 24, 205 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10530 - 021 - 02638 - w" type="journal article" year="2022">
Mori 
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FEEDFD92FE27013D" box="[363,420,513,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">et al.</emphasis>
2022
</bibRefCitation>
). This constitutes the first report for both Madeira and the Canary Islands. Sequences matched identically to all available sequences on GenBank (
<figureCitation id="135D2A26FFB0FF92FC9CFDB5FC0A0119" box="[794,905,549,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,849,873]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,236,826]" captionTargetId="figure-34@1.[151,1436,236,826]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Maximum-likelihood tree of invasive terrestrial flatworms, based on COI sequences. Bootstrap values are presented only for main clades. Countries are indicated after GenBank accession number. Red: specimens sequenced in this study. A. Caenoplana coerulea tree. B. Endeavouria septemlineata tree. C. Obama nungara tree." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501323" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501323/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Figure 1C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD936A3FFB0FF92FF41FDD9FAAA001D" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">
It is noteworthy that some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C664D20FFB0FF92FDF5FDD9FD6E0145" authorityName="Carbayo, Alvarez-Presas, Jones &amp; Riutort" authorityYear="2016" box="[627,749,585,609]" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Obama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="nungara">
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FDF5FDD9FD6E0145" box="[627,749,585,609]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">O. nungara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C664D20FFB0FF92FCA6FDDAFC520145" baseAuthorityName="Hyman" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[800,977,585,609]" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Endeavouria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="septemlineata">
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FCA6FDDAFC520145" box="[800,977,585,609]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">E. septemlineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were found in well-preserved humid laurel forest. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF74B52FFB0FF92FED7FDFDFDE401A1" author="Lago-Barcia, D. &amp; Gonzalez-Lopez, J. R. &amp; Fernandez-Alvarez, F. A." box="[337,615,621,645]" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" pagination="197 - 200" refId="ref2982" refString="Lago-Barcia, D., Gonzalez-Lopez, J. R. &amp; Fernandez-Alvarez, F. A. (2020) The invasive land flatworm Obama nungara (Platyhelminthes: Geoplanidae) reaches a natural environment in the oceanic island of Sao Miguel (Acores). Zootaxa, 4830 (1), 197 - 200. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4830.1.9" type="journal article" year="2020">
Lago-Barcia 
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FE59FDFEFD9401A1" box="[479,535,621,645]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">et al.</emphasis>
(2020)
</bibRefCitation>
found 
<taxonomicName id="4C664D20FFB0FF92FD3EFDFDFCB601A1" authorityName="Carbayo, Alvarez-Presas, Jones &amp; Riutort" authorityYear="2016" box="[696,821,621,645]" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Obama" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="nungara">
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FD3EFDFDFCB601A1" box="[696,821,621,645]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">O. nungara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingRegion id="49A2F841FFB0FF92FCDDFDFDFC2401A1" box="[859,935,621,645]" country="Portugal" name="Acores" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Azores</collectingRegion>
in a natural area comprised of low scrubland and prairies. 
<taxonomicName id="4C664D20FFB0FF92FEA0FD01FD8D018D" authorityName="Moseley" authorityYear="1877" box="[294,526,657,681]" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Caenoplana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="coerulea">
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FEA0FD01FD8D018D" box="[294,526,657,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Caenoplana coerulea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingRegion id="49A2F841FFB0FF92FDB2FD01FD0E018D" box="[564,653,657,681]" country="Portugal" name="Madeira" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Madeira</collectingRegion>
was found in a scrubland near a beach. Although in the 
<collectingRegion id="49A2F841FFB0FF92FB7DFD01FA1E018D" box="[1275,1437,657,681]" country="Spain" name="Canarias" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Canary Islands</collectingRegion>
this species is predominantly found in anthropic areas, it has also been found in a subterranean ecosystem (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF74B52FFB0FF92FA93FD25FF5201D5" author="Suarez, D. &amp; Martin, S. &amp; Naranjo, M." pageId="2" pageNumber="449" pagination="67 - 74" refId="ref3441" refString="Suarez, D., Martin, S. &amp; Naranjo, M. (2018) First report of the invasive alien species Caenoplana coerulea Moseley, 1877 (Platyhelminthes, Tricladida, Geoplanidae) in the subterranean environment of the Canary Islands. Subterranean Biology, 26, 67 - 74. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / SUBTBIOL. 26.25921" type="journal article" year="2018">
Suárez 
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FAE0FD26FA1E01E9" box="[1382,1437,693,717]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). Overall, this suggests that contrary to continental settings where land planarians are typically found in anthropic ecosystems, such as gardens or greenhouses (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF74B52FFB0FF92FD07FD6DFC200031" author="Alvarez-Presas, M. &amp; Mateos, E. &amp; Tudo, A. &amp; Jones, H. &amp; Riutort, M." box="[641,931,765,791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" pagination="430" refId="ref2399" refString="Alvarez-Presas, M., Mateos, E., Tudo, A., Jones, H. &amp; Riutort, M. (2014) Diversity of introduced terrestrial flatworms in the Iberian Peninsula: A cautionary tale. PeerJ, 2, e 430. https: // doi. org / 10.7717 / peerj. 430" type="journal article" year="2014">
Álvarez-Presas 
<emphasis id="B912EAB1FFB0FF92FCAAFD6EFCE10031" box="[812,866,765,789]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
), in oceanic island systems invasive flatworms have the potential to extend their ranges into natural areas, thus posing a threat to endemic invertebrate fauna.
</paragraph>
